Brexit ? See it from another way !¶

Tianzhu Qin¶

1. Introduction¶

Brexit is just around the corner, with the whole UK discussing, debating and fighting here and there. Meanwhile, In the Internet, especially in Twitter, things are also not peaceful. Everytime we search anything related to brexit, hundreds of new tweets will fill our screen. Since we have already been exposed to the complecated and boring articles for a long time, the essay aims to dig out the hidden implication in shorter but flexible tweets and information from their generators. The essay flows as below:

  • Introducing data: Scrapping, Deduplicating and Processing
  • Analyzing tweets: Time, Text and Sentiment
  • Exploring geography: Map Distribution and Prediction Model

Due to GitHub's uploading limits, the whole project can only be showed here:

def draw_cloud(word_freq):
    """Generate word cloud
    Args:
        word_freq:
            A dict. A dict of words and their frequencies.
    
    Python 3.7 may need more efforts to install wordcloud package well.
    """ 
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 40))

    # set background photo
    mask_img = imageio.imread("britainflag.png")
    image_colors = ImageColorGenerator(mask_img)

    # draw cloud
    cloud = WordCloud(collocations=False,
                      max_words=200,
                      background_color='white',
                      mask=mask_img,
                      ).generate_from_frequencies(word_freq)
    
    # draw color
    plt.imshow(cloud.recolor(color_func=image_colors))
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

draw_cloud(word_count)

Word cloud is made by acquiring Twitter text data about Brexit.

From the graph we can see the words related and the size of word implies the importance of it. Here Theresa May, Deal and Corbyn are called lots of times concerning Brexit in Twitter.

2. Data Exploration¶

2.1 Scrap Data¶

The essay scrapped data by Twitter API and stored everything in an Elasticsearch Database, which is No-SQL Database thatis really good to nested data structure, i.e. lots of attributes and attributes in attributes. For presentation, The essay created a remote ELasticsearch Database in AWS server, with only data on show. The whole data is above 15 GB in Database and incredible larger in json files.

2.2 Deduplicate Data¶

Due to strict API rule by Twitter, the essay can only acquire a few thousand tweets every 15 minutes, but tweets concerning brexit is more than twenty thousand within one hour for most cases. The essay therefore implemented more than one API crawler and ran them successively. Thus, data might confront with duplications when adding them all.

2.3 Process Data¶

For further research and presentation, the essay makes four different files to store the useful information separately, i.e. tweets_data, users_data, tweets_info, tweets_text, which are all pickle file remaining their python structures. They will be presented below.

  • Processing text data, the essay calculate the sentiment score of each text by textblob module, which uses a Naive Bayes Analyzer.

  • Acquiring exact location where the user belongs to, the essay utilizes Google Map API to search each location text input by the user themseleves, which is not standerlized. The API returns the city, country and geo-point data of it for further research.

dates = id_time.date.unique()

sns.set(style="white", palette="muted", color_codes=True) # choose color
f, axes = plt.subplots(len(dates), 1, figsize=(10, 15), sharex=True) # share x axis
sns.despine(left=True)

hours = range(24)
full_day = []
for i, date in enumerate(dates):
    # group each day and get its counts, if no then update to 0
    df_dict = id_time[id_time["date"]==date].groupby("hour").size().to_dict()
    for key in hours:
        if key not in df_dict:
            df_dict.update({key:0})
    df = pd.Series(df_dict).reset_index().rename(columns={"index":"hour",0:date})
    # bar plot at one ax
    g = sns.barplot("hour", date, data=df, ax=axes[i], palette="Blues")
    g.set_xlabel("")
    g.set_ylabel(date, rotation=0)
    # update the full day
    if (df[date]!=0).all():
        full_day.append(date)

plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.96)
plt.suptitle("Data Time Distributions (Nov.)",)
plt.setp(axes, yticks=[])
plt.xticks(np.arange(24), tuple(hours))
plt.xlim([-1, 24])
plt.xlabel("Time")
plt.show()

def heat_map(matrix, order, title="", cmap=plt.cm.gray_r):
    """Draw the heatmap.

    Args:
        matrix:
            A np.ndarray. Matrix to plot as a heatmap.
        order:
            A np.ndarray. Order of languages.
        title:
            A string. The title of this graph, default to "".
        cmap:
            A color map. Default to plt.cm.gray_r.
    """
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 20))
    cax = ax.matshow(matrix, cmap=cmap)
    fig.colorbar(cax, fraction=0.045)
    
    # show the language name
    names = np.arange(len(order))
    ax.set_xticks(names)
    ax.set_xticklabels(order, rotation=90)
    ax.set_yticks(names)
    ax.set_yticklabels(order)
    ax.set_title(title, y=-0.05, fontsize=20);

def draw_heat_map(list_need, list_all, title="", cmap=plt.cm.gray_r):
    """Draw the heatmap by the given listed items and the items all documents list.

    Args:
        list_need:
            A list. The items in list will be plot as axis.
        list_all:
            A list. The documents that items happen in.
        title:
            A string. The title of this graph, default to "".
        cmap:
            A color map. Default to plt.cm.gray_r.
    """
    
    # first construct a matrix to fill
    co_matrix = np.zeros(shape=(len(list_need), len(list_need)))
    for item1 in list_need:
        for item2 in list_need[list_need.index(item1)+1:]: # only iterate the left part
            count_co = 0 # numerator
            count1 = 0 # denominator
            count2 = 0 # denominator
            for mention in list_all: # iterate whole list
                flag1 = item1 in mention
                flag2 = item2 in mention

                if flag1: # calculate how many times item1 happens.
                    count1 += 1
                if flag2: # calculate how many times item2 happens.
                    count2 += 1
                if flag1 and flag2: #calculate how many times both happen.
                    count_co += 1

            if count1 > 0 and count2 >0:
                # co-use/(count of language1^0.5 * count of language2^0.5)
                cs = count_co / (np.sqrt(count1) * np.sqrt(count2))
                co_matrix[list_need.index(item1)][list_need.index(item2)] = cs
                co_matrix[list_need.index(item2)][list_need.index(item1)] = cs

    # get all information in need
    cs_L = np.diag(np.sum(co_matrix,1)) - co_matrix
    cs_D, cs_V = np.linalg.eigh(cs_L)
    cs_V = cs_V[:,np.argsort(cs_D)]

    # permutation in the order of Fiedler vector elements
    fiedler = np.argsort(cs_V[:,1])
    cs_need = [list_need[i] for i in fiedler]
    cs_matrix = co_matrix[fiedler][:,fiedler]

    heat_map(cs_matrix, cs_need, title=title, cmap=cmap)

formal_name = {} # get the official county name
country_name = {} # get the official country name
for key, value in user_location.items():
    if value != []:
        formal = value[0]["address_components"][0]["long_name"] # county name
        country = value[0]["address_components"][-1]["long_name"] # country name
        # reduce the worthless location name
        if not formal.isdigit() and "#" not in formal and "-" not in formal and formal != "":
            formal_name[key] = formal
        if not country.isdigit() and "#" not in country and "-" not in country and country != "":
            country_name[key] = country

# pair the official name, by input of user, or "" if failed to pair
id_location = users_data.copy()
for user in id_location:
    location = user["location"].lower() # ignore case
    if location in formal_name:
        user["location"] = formal_name[location]
    else:
        user["location"] = ""

    if location in country_name:
        user["country"] = country_name[location]
    else:
        user["country"] = ""

id_location = pd.DataFrame(id_location)
# join the two dataframe by userid
cross_table = id_time.set_index("userid").join(id_location.set_index("id"))
cross_table = cross_table[cross_table["location"]!=""] # forget the unknown ones
# get the mean of sensitive for each location/country
location_sentiment = cross_table[["sentiment", "location"]].groupby("location").mean()
country_sentiment = cross_table[["sentiment", "country"]].groupby("country").mean()
location_X = cross_table[["location", "sentiment", "time",
                          "favorite_count", "retweet_count"]].groupby("location")
location_X = location_X.mean().join(pd.DataFrame(location_X.size().rename("count")))

def draw_map(sentiment, uk=True):
    """Draw the sentiment distribution for map
    
    Args:
        sentiment:
            A dataframe. The sentiment for each location.

    """
    
    if uk:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16,12))
        m = Basemap(
            projection='stere',
            llcrnrlon=-11, # left lower point lon
            llcrnrlat=49, # left lower point lat
            urcrnrlon=5,# right upper point lon
            urcrnrlat=61, # right upper point lat
            lon_0=0, # center point lon
            lat_0=51   # center point lat
        )
        m.shadedrelief() # set background
        m.readshapefile("britainmap/gadm36_GBR_2", 'areas')
        attr = "NAME_2" # further join index
        cmap = plt.get_cmap('seismic') # picture params
        pad = 0.05
        shrink = 1
        orient = "vertical"
        ax.set_title("UK sentiments towards Brexit",  fontsize=20)
    else:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(18,20))
        m = Basemap(lon_0=0, projection='robin')
        m.drawmapboundary(color='w') # set background
        m.readshapefile("worldmap/ne_10m_admin_0_countries_lakes", 'areas')
        attr = "NAME" # further join index
        cmap = plt.get_cmap('Blues') # picture params
        ax.axhspan(0, 1000 * 1800, facecolor='w', edgecolor='w', zorder=2)
        pad = 0.0005
        shrink = 0.5
        orient = "horizontal"
        ax.set_title("World sentiments towards Brexit",  y=-0.003, fontsize=20)

    df_poly = pd.DataFrame({
            'shapes': [Polygon(np.array(shape), True) for shape in m.areas],
            'area': [area[attr] for area in m.areas_info]
        })
    df_poly = df_poly.set_index("area").join(sentiment) # join the polygon and input sentiment-location
    # draw the colors to map by location polygon and the color degree by its sentiment
    pc = PatchCollection(df_poly.shapes, zorder=2)
    norm = Normalize()
    pc.set_facecolor(cmap(norm(df_poly['sentiment'].fillna(0).values)))
    ax.add_collection(pc)
    # draw the color bar to new mapper
    mapper = matplotlib.cm.ScalarMappable(norm=norm, cmap=cmap)
    mapper.set_array(df_poly['sentiment'])
    fig.colorbar(mapper, fraction=0.045, orientation=orient, shrink=shrink, pad=pad)

4.2 Brexit Prediction Model¶

The essay takes all the location and sentiment data to make prediction model of Brexit. I divide the UK into electoral districts, and take the referendum data (Brexitvote.csv) of each district as ground truth (https://data.london.gov.uk/dataset/eu-referendum-results). The steps are as below.

1. Aggregate the location, sentiment, retweets, favorites, time data into one dataframe
2. Group by the location (each electoral district) and take means of all rest
3. Calculate cosine similarity matrix with similarity of each row by each row
4. Use Spectral Co-Clustering to divide districts into two parts, one for Leave and one for Remain

# get real value and predicted value and makes confusion matrix
real_value = ["Leave" if i in brexit_counties else "Remain" for i in tickslabel]
pred_value = ["Leave" if i>=sum(model.biclusters_[0][0]) else "Remain" for i in range(len(real_value))]
cm = confusion_matrix(real_value, pred_value)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7,6))
ax.set_title('Confusion matrix', fontsize=16)
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, cmap="coolwarm")
ax.set_xticklabels(["Leave", "Remain"])
ax.set_yticklabels(["Leave", "Remain"])
ax.set_xlabel('Predicted Value', fontsize=15)
ax.set_ylabel('True Value', fontsize=15)

# calculate precision, recall, accuracy and F1
precision = cm[0][0] / (cm[0][0] + cm[1][0])
recall = cm[0][0] / (cm[0][0] + cm[0][1])
accuracy = (cm[0][0] + cm[1][1]) / sum(sum(cm))
f1 = 2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall)

print("Precision: %0.4f"%precision)
print("Recall:    %0.4f"%recall)
print("Accuracy:  %0.4f"%accuracy)
print("F1:        %0.4f"%f1)

Precision: 0.8082
Recall:    0.6020
Accuracy:  0.6187
F1:        0.6901

Compared with the ground truth from EU referendum, this method gives precision as high as around 0.8, with others not too bad.

In this sense, the essay introduces this method for further political preidiction. Politicians may acquire these data consistently and once related issues happenning, check which districts need more caring, and target them.

5. Conclusion¶

The essay holds 4,638,226 documents, with nested json format, acquired by my automatical scrapper by Twitter API, after deduplicating over one million. They have now been stored in my personal elasticsearch database, but showed as an example in AWS elasticsearch. With all these data, my main target is to find out whether Twitter can show different but valuable knowledge from normal press.

To achive this, the essay implements sentiment analysis of each text and recovers the location information by re-searching via GoogleMap API. For further study, the essay converts the whole data to five handy files.

The essay firstly presents the tweets information in elegant graphs and picks out the interesting points that favorites count and retweets count behave significantly to the opposite within one full day.

By fiedler heatmap, Leave/Remain group can be found, and the press are highlighted to its own part.

Under real world map, patterns of Commonwealth countries come out and the familiar EU Referendum distribution reappears magically, by conneting sentiments to each location.

At last, the essay introduces a clustering model, which gives high precision predicting which district will vote for Brexit. Government for gathering the public may take this method to plan initially who need more help.

It is evident to see there are many secrets hidden in tweets. With data analyzing, we dig out the interesting relationship, and provide a nice model.
